replies.text:
@AB-C1 The stove itself is a pretty substantial piece of kit. The body's made out of a 4' long piece of something like 20 to 24" diameter (Very) thick wall pipe layed horizontally on chunky solid legs. He then cut a strip out of the top of that and welded in about a 10" wide slab of steel plate to form a surface to cook on. The back plate and front door have got to be over an inch thick too, so with all that steel, the whole thing works like a fairly effective thermal mass all by itself, and in winter, never really get's down to room temperature. Even so, when we talked about it, he said that if he puts the lumps of stainless on top before it's first lit, the workshop feels like it actually takes longer to heat back up in the mornings than without them, so they must be absorbing a fairly large amount of energy. 

He told me that when the stainless is in the house it's usually still a bit too hot to touch without welding gloves the following morning, so it must be storing a pretty substantial amount of heat. I also remember asking why he didn't make a heatsink to sit on top of one so he could get the heat out quicker, and he told me there was no need, and that would most likely make the bungalow TOO warm at night.


Slightly annoyingly, I've never actually seen the stove lit, or the "Thermal accumulators" in use, so the only info I have on them is from when I was admiring his work during the visit after he'd built the stove, and the questions I thought to ask at the time. But as the weather can get pretty inhospitable over there in winter, I've not yet been nuts enough to go visit him during that time of year...... The idea of looking at the weather report and knowing you'll be having to dig your way out of the house through a snow drift AGAIN come the morning sounds just a bit too claustrophobic for my liking. :D
